<br>
It's a little more complicated than that Einstein.  Granted a country that can make a spacecraft most likely has the resources to create a ballistic missile, but you don't just put a nuke on a spacecraft and launch it at another country.  You'd honestly have more success just putting it on a fucking airplane...hell of a lot easier to navigate through the atmosphere don't you think?  How many countries have airplanes?  I sure as fuck don't think they all have ballistic missiles capable of striking a country thousands of miles away.  It's quite a bit more complex than you may think.<br>
<br>
I don't think the average American wants war.  Hell I don't want war, but I do think that there is a lot of things that, due to not revealing the sources of such, the general public is not aware of.  The UN has stated that Iraq is in violation of the UN Resolutions.  We KNOW that there are stockpiles of nerve agents that are missing.  I don't think Nukes are necessarily the biggest worry here, because the resources needed to create a nuke and a device to deliver the weapon are very difficult to come by.  Now a chemical or nerve agent such as VX is not really all that difficult to create or deliver when compared to a Nuclear Bomb.  Even easier is a biological agent such as anthrax or smallpox.  Those my friends are the true dangers in this time.  I believe that as time goes on a nuclear threat will become more and more prevalent, but for now the whole talk of whose gonna nuke who is really asinine.  <br>
<br>
As to what to do about Iraq?  Well...I think there comes a certain point where you have to put some faith in our elected leaders.  Congress gave President Bush the authority to act militarily and unilaterally against Iraq.  There obviously is more to the story than any of us really know.  I do know that regardless of what decision is made, when it is made, we as Americans need to support the soldiers that are going to do the job simply because they are following orders.  <br>
<br>
I say make all the damn web pages you want...sign all the petitions you like...enjoy the freedom to do so...that is the core of what America is.  In the words of Steven Decatur &quot;Our country, in dealing with other countries, may she always be right; but she is still our country right or wrong.&quot; <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub54.ezboard.com/bquelliousquaterstherebirth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=gimily>Gimily</A> at: 1/15/03 10:47:22 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub54.ezboard.com/bquelliousquaterstherebirth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=talzarbbh>Talzar BBH</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Froglok Dar Knight</span><br>  Posts: 31<br> <font color=#00CCFF>(1/15/03 10:42:31 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub54.ezboard.com/fquelliousquaterstherebirthfrm13.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=795.topic&index=51>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: OT - Opposed to the war with Iraq? Heres what you can do</span><hr size=1> Do you know what a really good movie was?  &quot;The Sum of All Fears&quot; I think was the exact title.  You do know that can happen five minutes from now, next week or in two years?  If you think that it can't you are extremely misinformed to put it a nice way.<br>
